`crates/` is the workspace root: a set of independent Rust binary/library crates implementing the ctx toolchain — the enforcement, generation, verification, and sandboxing layers that together let an agent read, write, summarize, and check a repo under context-discipline. Depending on this level gets you the whole toolchain's separately-versioned components; there is no shared code here, only Cargo workspace membership.

The crates split cleanly by lifecycle stage: `ctx-core` is the shared kernel (path safety, hash-sidecar schema) consumed by `ctx-scan` and `ctx-context`. `ctx-access` is the sole enforced read/write path for agents. `ctx-scan` detects staleness and drives regeneration; `ctx-summarize` is the LLM-backed generator invoked by that regeneration; `ctx-context` serves the resulting chain read-only to the CLI/hook layer. `ctx-check` and `ctx-verify` are independent verification brokers (cargo/clippy/script diagnostics as JSON), overlapping in purpose but not sharing code — a change to one's report schema does not imply a change to the other's. `ctx-cage` is orthogonal: process sandboxing for tool execution and API egress, unrelated to the `.ctx` pipeline.

The cross-crate coupling that matters: `ctx-summarize`'s rollup input format and `.context` mirror-path convention must stay aligned with what `ctx-context` and `ctx-scan` expect on disk, since all three read/write the same `.context/` tree independently rather than through a shared library — there is no compile-time enforcement of this, only convention. Similarly, `ctx-access` delegates all gating decisions to `ctx-core` but nothing enforces that `ctx-summarize` or `ctx-scan` writes go through `ctx-access`'s gate; they write directly.

No `intent.md` exists at this level, so no divergence can be assessed.